# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afritada
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afritada/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:afritada/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:afritada/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:afritada/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:afritada/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:afritada/alaminos-longganisa] It is made with ground lean pork, ground pork fat, brown sugar, coarse salt, saltpeter, black pepper, bay leaf, vinegar, and garlic in hog casings.
[src:afritada/alaminos-longganisa] It is slightly sour, garlicky taste, typically bright yellow or orange due to the use of *achuete* seeds, made in bite-sized pieces.
[src:afritada/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is named after the Spanish “longaniza,” and is sometimes used interchangeably with the chorizo.
[src:afritada/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is a type of local sausage with two major types—the recado, with a more savory flavor, and the hamonado, with a sweet taste.
[src:afritada/alaminos-longganisa] Unlike other longganisa variants, the Alaminos longganisa's segments of the sausage are uniquely divided by small pieces of coconut leaf midribs (sometimes mistaken for toothpicks), making it easily identifiable.
[src:afritada/alaminos-longganisa] Each sausage string usually has six segments and is traditionally tied at the end with a length of buli palm fiber.
[src:afritada/alaminos-longganisa] The sausages are celebrated in an annual "Longganisa Festival" in Alaminos.
[src:afritada/alfajor] An ***alfajor*** or ***alajú*** (Spanish pronunciation: [alfaˈxoɾ], plural *alfajores*) is a traditional confection.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Originally from present-day Spain, it is found now in Argentina, Bolivia, Southern Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Ecuador, El Salvador, Southern France, Paraguay, Peru, the Philippines, Uruguay, and Venezuela.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The alfajor was born in Iberia during the rule of al-Andalus.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The Spanish alfajor is produced in the form of a small cylinder and is sold either individually or in boxes containing several pieces.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Traditional alfajores in Argentina, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn flour joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:afritada/alfajor] More modern "industrial" varieties in Uruguay and Argentina, are coated with dark or white chocolate (many *alfajores* are sold in "black" and "white" versions), or simply covered with powdered sugar.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The word had been introduced into Spanish dictionaries in the 14th century.
[src:afritada/alfajor] A similar sweet called *alaú* is found in the Arabic-Hispanic cookbook Kitab al-Tabikh, by an anonymous author.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The Spanish grammarian Nebrija noted the word for the first time in his Latin-Spanish Dictionary (1495) as: *alfaxor* or *alaxur*.
[src:afritada/alfajor] In the 12th century, Raimundo Martin describes in his book *Vocabulista* another possible etymology of the Hispano-Arabic *fasur*, meaning "nectar".
[src:afritada/alfajor] The publication of historical dictionaries of the Spanish language allows one to document both forms of the original *alajur*, written as *alajú* and *alfajor*.
[src:afritada/alfajor] *Alajur* and multiple geographic variations are sweets made of a paste of almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs and honey.
[src:afritada/alfajor] In the Americas, the word *alfajor* was not known until the 19th century.
[src:afritada/alfajor] In Spain, there are a variety of different recipes for preparing *alfajores*, but the most traditional contain flour, honey, almonds and several spices, such as cinnamon.
[src:afritada/alfajor] *Alfajores* are most commonly sold around Christmas.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The traditional Spanish *alfajor* has been produced in Medina-Sidonia (where it is called an *alajú*) since ancient times, and the recipe has been traditionally handed down from father to son.
[src:afritada/alfajor] In this town, there is an account of Mariano Pardo de Figueroa, writing under the pen name Dr.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Thebussem, wherein he wrote that on 2 July 1487, Enrique de Guzmán, second count of Medina Sidonia, ordered the council and majors of the region to send to Malaga 50 cows, 50 oxen, 200 calves and provision of *alajú* from his city.
[src:afritada/alfajor] On 15 September 2004, protected geographical indication was ratified by the *Consejo de agricultura y pesca de la junta de Andalucía* and published in the *Official Journal of the European Union* as *Alfajor de Medina Sidonia* on 6 March 2007.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The regulations of the Andalusian Ministry of Agriculture allow the use of only pure honey, almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs, sugar, flour and spices, such as aniseed, sesame, cilantro, cloves and cinnamon.
[src:afritada/alfajor] These *alfajores* are meant to be presented in a cylindrical shape, with a minimum weight of 30 grams (1.1 oz) each, and with a minimum size of about 7 centimetres (2.8 in) in length and a diameter of 1.5 centimetres (0.59 in).
[src:afritada/alfajor] Each of them will be protected with a wrapping paper, and the ends made an ornament in a spiral shape with a ribbon out of the same paper.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Once individually wrapped, they may be packaged in wood or cardboard boxes, but never in plastic.
[src:afritada/alfajor] In the province of Cuenca, Spain, where the *alfajor* is called *alajú,* it is made with almond, honey and figs, wrapped in a wafer.
[src:afritada/alfajor] In Puerto Rico, they underwent creolization, lost their almond and gained ground cassava.
[src:afritada/alfajor] They can take varying amounts of sugar and spices.
[src:afritada/alfajor] It is possible that Puerto Rico's most common version of this dessert (the South American version with dulce de leche) reached Puerto Rico from Venezuela, but the opposite is also possible.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Depending on region some add cornstarch, citrus zest, ginger and honey, filled with chocolate, vanilla cream, dulce de leche, fruit paste, or coconut.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The filling can be mixed with almonds, sesame seeds, coconut flakes, or sprinkles.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Traditional "alfajores" in Chile, Argentina,and Uruguay consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn starch joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:afritada/alfajor] These are also known as a *Chilean Oreo*.
[src:afritada/alfajor] One variation is called "*alfajor de nieve*" (snow alfajor) and has a white coating consisting of a mixture of egg whites and sugar.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Most *alfajores* come packaged in aluminium foil.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Alfajores are made in various diameters and are consumed as snacks.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The *alfajor* has been manufactured and consumed since colonial times in the territories that today belong to Argentina.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The filling is usually dulce de leche, although there are many variations.
[src:afritada/alfajor] They can be covered with powder sugar (the traditional ones), glazed sugar (Santafesinos or "de nieve"), grated coconut or chocolate.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Argentina is one of the world's largest consumers of alfajores, both in total numbers and in per capita calculations, consuming more than a billion alfajores a year.
[src:afritada/alfajor] One important Argentine alfajor is the alfajor de Santa Fe or the alfajor santafesino, which has three puff pastry layers adhered to one another with dulce de leche and glazed all over.
[src:afritada/alfajor] This alfajor is closely linked to the history of the city of Santa Fe.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Colonel Néstor Fernández from Santa Fe took it to the Battle of Caseros in 1851.
[src:afritada/alfajor] It became so popular with the army that General Justo José de Urquiza had a weekly shipment of these alfajores delivered to his estancia in San José de Entre Ríos.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The production of Santa Fe alfajores began in 1851 in a shop located on the southwest corner of San Jerónimo and 3 de Febrero streets, a few meters from the Cabildo (where the Santa Fe Government House currently stands).
[src:afritada/alfajor] These alfajores became known throughout the country after the 24 writers of the constitution, who, after living in Santa Fe for six months, took this dessert home as a souvenir.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Today, it is a heritage of the city of Santa Fe and is handcrafted in that city and its surrounding areas.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The nickname "Merengo" gave rise to a brand of alfajores.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The Cordobes alfajor is filled with fruit jellies (generally of quince).
[src:afritada/alfajor] In addition, there is the Rogel, similar to the Santa Fe but bigger (the size of a small cake) and a variety from Tucuman known as a clarita, with two crunchy cookies and filled with a jelly made up of sugar molasses.
[src:afritada/alfajor] In Argentina, alfajores made up of cornflour are very consumed as well (covers made up of maize starch, filled with dulce de leche and grated coconut around the filling).
[src:afritada/alfajor] Mass-production of alfajores traces back to the Atlantic coast of Argentina in the 1950s.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Brands such as Havanna and Balcarce, and as many as 30 others, have been introduced into shops and supermarkets.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Statistics of the year 2021 shows that inhabitants of Argentina consume 6 million alfajores per day.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Two types of alfajores are found in Chile.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The first type of alfajor, similar to the one of corn flour prepared in other countries of Latin America, is prepared over all the territory of Chile, but mainly in the central area of Chile.
[src:afritada/alfajor] It is known as "candy of corn flour" or, more typically, "chilenitos".
[src:afritada/alfajor] The chilenitos are manufactured with corn flour or other types of flour and tend to be simpler and smaller than the other alfajores.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The second type of alfajor, considered the true traditional alfajor of the country and known as "chilean alfajor", is mainly prepared in the southern areas of Chile, generally for the patriotic festivities of September.
[src:afritada/alfajor] It is prepared with two hojarascas (a thin and firm cookie) that, since they are previously baked, acquire a curved form.
[src:afritada/alfajor] They are adhered to each other with dark brown sugar, panela, manjar or with confectioners cream.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Optionally, they can be garnished in the end of the filling with grated coconut as it is the case of the alfajores filled with manjar or with ground nuts.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Alfajores made their arrival to the Viceroyalty of Peru, the largest administrative district of the Spanish Empire in South America in the 16th century, and have been popular since, especially the artisanal types.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Alfajor de Trujillo is a type of alfajor from Trujillo.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The *alfajor de Trujillo* has several layers and it can be of different sizes and shapes as round or square.
[src:afritada/alfajor] It is made mainly with products as flour, butter, eggs and milk, filled with milk candy, some pineapple sweet and in some cases peanuts, with cookies within its layers.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The most famous company manufacturing this products in Trujillo is Dulcería Castañeda, which has locations in Trujillo and Lima and has been making them since 1925.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The mass of the alfajor is made of flour, eggs, margarine, salt, and water.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The filling is made with figs, quince, walnuts, blancmange.
[src:afritada/alfajor] It is one of the products presented in the Gastronomic Fair in Trujillo.
[src:afritada/alfajor] Another variant of the alfajor de trujillo is King Kong milk candy, which is made in both Trujillo and Lambayeque.
[src:afritada/alfajor] According to Guinness World Records, the biggest *alfajor* in the world, measuring almost 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) in diameter and 80 centimetres (31 in) in height and weighing 464 kilograms (1,023 lb), was made on 11 December 2010 in Minas, Lavalleja Department, Uruguay.
[src:afritada/alfajor] The giant *alfajor* was made to mark the celebration of Uruguay's first National Alfajor Festival.
[src:afritada/alfajor] More than 30 people participated in the preparation of the record-breaking *alfajor*.
[src:afritada/aligue-fried-rice] It is a variant of *sinangag* (garlic fried rice) and is similar to bagoong fried rice, which uses *bagoong* (shrimp paste).
[src:afritada/ampaw] Another Filipino word, *ampaw (also spelled as angpao* or *ampao*, from Philippine Hokkien Chinese: 紅包; Pe̍h-ōe-jī: *âng-pau*; lit.
[src:afritada/ampaw] 'red packet'), referring to Chinese red envelopes should not be confused with this term, as they are homonyms.
[src:afritada/ampaw] Ampaw is made with cooked white rice (usually leftovers).
[src:afritada/ampaw] It is dried in the sun for around four hours.
[src:afritada/ampaw] They are then fried in hot oil to make them puff up.
[src:afritada/ampaw] The oil is drained thoroughly after frying.
[src:afritada/ampaw] The sugar glazing is cooked separately using muscovado sugar or molasses (or corn syrup), salt, butter, and vinegar or calamansi juice.
[src:afritada/ampaw] The glazing is poured unto the puffed rice and mixed until the grains are evenly coated.
[src:afritada/ampaw] It is then allowed to cool and shaped into the desired form before it fully hardens.
[src:afritada/ampaw] They are usually cut into square or rectangular blocks or molded into balls.
[src:afritada/ampaw] Traditional ampaw is white in color, but many modern variants are dyed in various colors to appeal more to children.
[src:afritada/ampaw] Ampaw can be easily modified with added ingredients.
[src:afritada/ampaw] Examples include roasted peanuts, pinipig (toasted young rice), and chocolate.
[src:afritada/ampaw] Ampaw can also be made with other types of rice, like brown rice or black rice.
[src:afritada/anatto] The color of annatto comes from various carotenoid pigments, mainly bixin and norbixin, found in the reddish waxy coating of the seeds.
[src:afritada/anatto] The condiment is typically prepared by grinding the seeds to a powder or paste.
[src:afritada/anatto] Similar effects can be obtained by extracting some of the color and flavor principles from the seeds with hot water, oil, or lard, which are then added to the food.
[src:afritada/anatto] Annatto and its extracts are widely used artisanally and industrially as a coloring agent in many processed food products, such as cheeses, dairy spreads, butter and margarine, custards, cakes and other baked goods, potatoes, snack foods, breakfast cereals, smoked fish, and sausages.
[src:afritada/anatto] In these uses, annatto is a natural alternative to synthetic food coloring compounds, but it has been linked to rare cases of food-related allergies.
[src:afritada/anatto] The annatto tree *B. orellana* is believed to originate in tropical regions from Mexico to Brazil.
[src:afritada/anatto] It was probably not initially used as a food additive, but for other purposes, such as ritual and decorative body painting (still an important tradition in many Brazilian native tribes, such as the Wari'), sunscreen, insect repellent, and for medical purposes.
[src:afritada/anatto] It was used for Mexican manuscript painting in the 16th century.
[src:afritada/anatto] Men of the Tsàchila tribe in Ecuador are highly recognizable thanks to their traditional bright orange hair, which is achieved by using crushed seeds of annatto.
[src:afritada/anatto] It is believed they have been doing so for centuries.
[src:afritada/anatto] Annatto has been traditionally used as both a coloring and flavoring agent in various cuisines from Latin America, the Caribbean, the Philippines, and other countries where it was taken home by Spanish and Portuguese colonizers in the 16th century.
[src:afritada/anatto] It has various local names according to region.
[src:afritada/anatto] Its use has spread in historic times to other parts of the world, and it was incorporated in local culinary traditions of many countries outside the Americas.
[src:afritada/anatto] Ground annatto seeds, often mixed with other seeds or spices, are used in the form of paste or powder for culinary use, especially in Latin American, Jamaican, Belizean, Chamorro, Vietnamese, and Filipino cuisines.
[src:afritada/anatto] In Mexican and Belizean cuisines, it is used to make the spice *recado rojo*.
[src:afritada/anatto] In Venezuela, annatto is used in the preparation of *hallacas, huevos pericos*, and other traditional dishes.
[src:afritada/anatto] In Puerto Rico, it is often simmered in oil or ground with seasonings and herbs to make *sazón* or used to make *pasteles*, *arroz con gandules*, and several other dishes, where it is one of the main ingredients.
[src:afritada/anatto] Annatto paste is an important ingredient of *cochinita pibil*, the slow-roasted pork dish popular in Mexico.
[src:afritada/anatto] It is also a key ingredient in the drink *tascalate* from Chiapas, Mexico.
[src:afritada/anatto] In the Philippines, it is used for the sauce of *pancit palabok*.
[src:afritada/anatto] Annatto may provide an earthy, sweet and peppery flavor.
[src:afritada/anatto] Annatto is commonly used to impart a yellow or orange color to many industrialized and semi-industrialized foods, including cheese, ice cream, bakery products, desserts, fruit fillings, yogurt, butter, oils, margarines, processed cheese, and fat-based products.
[src:afritada/anatto] In the United States, annatto extract is listed as a color additive "exempt from certification" and is informally considered to be a natural coloring.
[src:afritada/anatto] Foods colored with annatto may declare the coloring in the statement of ingredients as "colored with annatto" or "annatto color".
[src:afritada/anatto] In the European Union, it is identified by the E number E160b.
[src:afritada/anatto] As the pigment is carried in the cream, skimming the milk, which some farmers did to make butter or to sell it separately, the lesser-quality cheese from such milk would be white.
[src:afritada/anatto] While masking the white hues of the cheese during the winter was the primary reason, annatto was also used in cheeses like Red Leicester to stand out from popular cheddar cheeses and to make customers believe that the darker orange hues meant richer milk which in turn meant tastier cheese.
[src:afritada/anatto] To fool the consumer, the cheesemakers introduced colorants to imitate the more intense colors of the finer summer cheese.
[src:afritada/anatto] Initially these colors came from saffron, marigold, and carrot juice, but later annatto came into use.
[src:afritada/anatto] In the 17th century, the Dutch, who had established colonies in Guyana, traded in food, particularly an orange-red natural colorant, annatto, with the indigenous communities.
[src:afritada/anatto] Zeeland traders under the authority of the West India Company bought annatto from the inhabitants of the coastal regions of Guyana and Suriname and sold it in the Netherlands as *verw* ('paint').
[src:afritada/anatto] One contemporaneous description comes from Adriaen van Berkel, in a book published in 1695, though he does not mention whether it was used in cheese.
[src:afritada/anatto] The earliest known documentation of annatto's use in cheese is in a 1743 Dutch volume *Huishoudelyk Woordboek* (*Household Dictionary*), according to American scientist Paul Kindstedt of the University of Vermont.
[src:afritada/anatto] Other historical documents from the period confirm that annatto (then called "orleaan" or "orleans") was being used to color cheese by the mid-18th century.
[src:afritada/anatto] England is another country that has used annatto to color its cheeses; colorants have been added to Gloucester cheese as early as the 16th century to allow inferior cheese to masquerade as the best Double Gloucester, with annatto later being used for that purpose.
[src:afritada/anatto] This usage was subsequently adopted in other parts of the UK, for cheeses such as Cheshire and Red Leicester, as well as colored Cheddar made in Scotland.
[src:afritada/anatto] Many cheddars are produced in both white and red (orange) varieties, the only difference between the two being the presence of annatto as a coloring.
[src:afritada/anatto] That practice has extended to many modern processed cheese products, such as American cheese and Velveeta.
[src:afritada/anatto] Cheeses from other countries also use annatto, including Mimolette from France and Leyden from the Netherlands.
[src:afritada/anatto] The yellow to orange color is produced by the chemical compounds bixin and norbixin, which are classified as carotenoids.
[src:afritada/anatto] The fat-soluble color in the crude extract is called bixin, which can then be saponified into water-soluble norbixin.
[src:afritada/anatto] This dual solubility property of annatto is rare for carotenoids.
[src:afritada/anatto] The seeds contain 4.5–5.5% pigment, which consists of 70–80% bixin.
[src:afritada/anatto] Unlike beta-carotene, another well-known carotenoid, annatto-based pigments are not vitamin A precursors.
[src:afritada/anatto] The more norbixin in an annatto preparation, the more yellow it is; a higher level of bixin gives it a more orange hue.
[src:afritada/anatto] As of 2025, the European Food Safety Authority does not list annatto among common food allergens.
[src:afritada/anatto] In 2009, annatto was not among the "Big Eight" substances causing the hypersensitivity reactions responsible for more than 90% of food-related allergic reactions.
[src:afritada/anatto] A 2025 review reported that annatto condiments and colorants are safe for most people when used in typical food amounts, but rarely may cause allergic reactions, such as hives and possibly anaphylaxis.
